-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
NMR-Solver (retrieval methodology) + SimNMR-PubChem (optional index corpus)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The spectrum-similarity retrieval in moltrace.spectroscopy.similarity follows the
methodology of NMR-Solver: Jin, Y.; Wang, J.-J.; Xu, F.; Ji, X.; Gao, Z.;
Zhang, L.; Ke, G.; Zhu, R.; E, W. "NMR-Solver: Automated Structure Elucidation
via Large-Scale Spectral Matching and Physics-Guided Fragment Optimization."
arXiv:2509.00640 (2025); Nat. Commun. The Gaussian-smoothed encoding and the
Kuhn-Munkres set-similarity score are implemented from the published equations,
not from any copyrighted text.

SimNMR-PubChem (optional large-scale index corpus): Hugging Face dataset
yqj01/SimNMR-PubChem (~106M PubChem-derived simulated spectra), distributed under
the MIT license, which permits commercial indexing. Re-confirm the dataset card
terms before distributing a derived index. Underlying PubChem records are
produced by the U.S. National Library of Medicine (public domain in the U.S.).

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
AIST SDBS (qNMR purity validation reference -- NOT redistributed)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The qNMR purity calculators in moltrace.spectroscopy.qnmr were validated against
the Spectral Database for Organic Compounds (SDBS), National Institute of
Advanced Industrial Science and Technology (AIST), Japan
(https://sdbs.db.aist.go.jp). SDBS spectra of certified-purity compounds were
used for INTERNAL validation only (to confirm the published internal-standard
and PULCON equations recover certified purities to within 0.5 % absolute).

SDBS terms restrict redistribution: NO SDBS spectrum, table, or derived data
file is bundled with MolTrace or committed to this repository. The shipped
test-suite (tests/spectroscopy/test_qnmr_purity.py) validates the math with
documented worked examples and closed-loop synthetic spectra instead. The two
purity equations themselves are textbook metrology (see the qNMR references
below) and carry no SDBS-derived obligation.

qNMR purity methods: Pauli, G. F. et al. J. Med. Chem. 57, 9220 (2014),
doi:10.1021/jm500734a (internal-standard qNMR); Wider, G.; Dreier, L.
J. Am. Chem. Soc. 128, 2571 (2006), doi:10.1021/ja055336t (PULCON). Implemented
from the published equations, not from any copyrighted text.

